result.execSummary:
The defendant Judith Kaye Nylander was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Negligent Operation of Motor Vehicle, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.01(1).
  • Reckless Driving-Endanger Safety. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.   No operation of any motor vehicles unless defendant has completed a Drivers Safety Improvement Program and with approval of supervising agent. Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle if taking the prescriptions as prescribed by her treating physician.
Defendant is to comply with any rules/recommendations as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

3:50 pm case called. Defendant Judith Kaye Nylander in court with attorney Jeanne L. Zamzow.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Agreement has been reached-amend criminal complaint filed with court.   Amended Criminal Complaint Stated - Advised of offense and minimum/maximum penalty.  Receipt Admitted - Reading Waived.    Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Consequences explained for failure to abide by terms of PPDA. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea: No Contest to Counts 1 & Counts 2. Court accepts plea and enters JOC on Count 2-Stays JOC on Count 1. Count 1- Court accepts terms and conditions of PPDA.  Matter stayed for 12 months. Statement by defendant. COUNT 2- SWD and places the defendant on probation for a period of 1 year. CONDITIONS:  Maintain Absolute Sobriety, No Bars, Defendant not to ingest any impairing substances unless prescribed by a physician. Defendant is not to drive until a Drivers Safety Improvement Program has been completed and with Agent approval. Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle if taking the prescriptions as prescribed by her treating physician. Terms of Agent. Costs to be paid within 60 days or payment plan. Appeal Rights Given. Court reminds defendant regarding bond while on PPDA.
Plea/sentencing hearing on September 3, 2014 at 03:45 pm.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician. Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle under any  circumstances if taking prescription medication.
Status conference on August 5, 2014 at 09:10 am.
